President Barack Obama has proclaimed May 2015 as National Mental Health Awareness Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights that approximately one in five American adults will experience a diagnosable mental health condition, and emphasizes the importance of access to quality and affordable care. The Affordable Care Act is mentioned as extending mental health benefits and protections to millions of Americans. The proclamation also mentions the government's commitment to funding research and expanding access to mental health services, particularly for veterans. It calls for an end to the stigma surrounding mental illness and encourages individuals to seek help when needed. The proclamation concludes by calling upon citizens, government agencies, organizations, healthcare providers, and research institutions to raise awareness about mental health and support the well-being of Americans.